Mayor Patricia De Lille says the City will go ahead with its court action to recoup millions lost during the build of the stadium. CAPE TOWN - The City of Cape Town says the construction industry transformation agreement between government and seven companies sends out the message that corruption by cartels is acceptable.Government on Tuesday gave a briefing on the agreement with seven companies who are found to have colluded around the construction of stadiums for the 2010 Fifa World Cup.Economic Development Minister Ebrahim Patel says more than 40 black-owned companies will benefit from the transformation commitments.Cape Town Mayor Patricia De Lille says the City will go ahead with its court action to recoup millions lost during the build of the Cape Town Stadium. On 2 December 2016 the Cape Town application was heard before court in Pretoria. And we ll continue to fight this matter in court until we recover the more than R430 million owed to the residents of the City of Cape Town. She adds government is sending out the wrong message. This violates the legal principle that we re all equal before the law. The City has filed a civil damages claim against three companies that colluded on the tender for the construction of the stadium.(Edited by Leeto M Khoza)